Goal:
Introduce a centralized bot command registry so that all Telegram bot service commands are declared in one place and can be managed consistently.

Context:
The project already has multiple Telegram command handlers and will continue to grow.
We need one explicit place where bot commands are defined and described centrally.

Target model:
- all service/admin/user-facing commands must be declared in one registry module
- each command entry must behave like enum-style metadata, not scattered string literals
- each command definition must include a flag that controls whether this command should be registered with Telegram via Bot API after startup
- command handlers may still live in focused handler modules, but command metadata must be centralized

Feature:
Centralized Bot Command Registry (MVP)

Scope:

1. Introduce one focused module for command definitions
   - all command names must live there
   - all Telegram-visible command metadata must live there
   - command definitions should behave like enum-style constants/entries, not ad-hoc strings

2. Each command definition must support at least:
   - command name
   - short description for Telegram command menu
   - scope/category if needed minimally
   - boolean flag like `register_after_startup` (name may differ if better)
     controlling whether the command should be sent to Telegram as a registered bot command

3. Existing command wiring should be updated to use centralized command definitions
   - remove duplicated command-name literals where practical
   - keep changes minimal
   - do not refactor unrelated business logic

4. Add a minimal startup-level integration point:
   - commands marked for Telegram registration can be collected from the registry
   - non-registered internal/service commands may still exist in the registry but should not be pushed to Telegram command menu

5. Keep handlers thin:
   - handler modules still own behavior
   - command registry owns metadata and canonical names

Cleanup rules:
- remove duplicated hardcoded command strings where replaced cleanly
- remove stale comments that suggest command metadata is defined locally in handlers
- do not keep parallel command registries
- do not leave a mix of centralized and ad-hoc command declarations without justification

Out of scope:
- role-aware Telegram command scoping by locale/user type unless trivially supported already
- dynamic per-user command registration
- web admin command management UI
- broad handler refactor
- command permissions redesign

Architecture constraints:
- keep implementation minimal
- prefer one focused registry module
- do not introduce a giant framework
- do not move business logic into the registry
- do not turn handler modules into metadata stores

Testing requirements:
- tests for registry integrity
- tests that command metadata is centrally discoverable
- tests that startup command collection respects the registration flag
- tests that existing handlers still use canonical command names from the registry where practical
- focused tests without Telegram runtime where possible

